comments.body:
Maybe use something like this to borrow as much structure as possible from PrivateMessage:

```
struct {
   /* there is no need to have a TargetedMessage.content_type, */
   /* because it is always `application` */
   opaque application_data<V>;

   /* you could trivially add padding here */
} TargetedMessageContent;

struct {
  opaque group_id<V>;
  uint64 epoch;
  uint32 recipient_leaf_index;
  opaque authenticated_data<V>;
} TargetedMessageAAD;

hpke_ciphertext = SealBase(target_public_key, TargetedMessageContext, TargetedMessageAAD, TargetedMessageContent)
```

I hope to have some performance numbers by the end of the year on large dictionaries in GroupContext.

The GroupContext is only included on signatures of external commits right?

```
struct {
    ProtocolVersion version = mls10;
    WireFormat wire_format;
    FramedContent content;
    select (FramedContentTBS.content.sender.sender_type) {
        case member:
        case new_member_commit:
            GroupContext context;
        case external:
        case new_member_proposal:
            struct{};
    };
} FramedContentTBS;
```

In terms of concrete action, it sounds like you are proposing:
- add text and maybe guidelines _in this document_ about the negative effects of very large dictionaries (worse in GroupContext)
- mention _in this document_ the idea of using hashes instead of data if the data can be stored elsewhere.
- write a new extension describing how to synchronize external data with hashes in the GroupContext (à la an external ratchet_tree)

issues.body:
We're having a small discussion on how to interpret the document over in the [mls-combiner repo](https://github.com/mlswg/mls-combiner/issues/6) on how to interpret this draft.

The question is on what the level of granularity is with which the `app_data_dictionary` can be updated. More concretely, what is the content of an AppDataUpdate proposal? Is it some information that the application/component then uses to update the state of the component in the `app_data_dictionary`? Or must it be the complete new content of the components entry in the `app_data_dictionary`, which then just replaces the old content?

@bitbltr please chime in here if I didn't present your side of the argument correctly.

comments.body:
@keks @kkohbrok I'm starting to see your perspective, especially with the following note in the draft:

> NOTE: An alternative design here would be to have the update operation simply set the new value for the app_data_dictionary GCE, instead of sending a diff.  This would be simpler in that the MLS stack wouldn't have to ask the application for the new state value, and would discourage applications from storing large state in the GroupContext directly...

My personal take on the issue is that opaque value updates is the only practical technique for the app_data_dictionary GCE in an environment that contains heterogeneous clients. If one client in the group doesn't understand how to update the value for a component ID and considers the update invalid, now the Group Context state cannot be agreed upon across all clients
